      "type": "html",
      "text": "\nApplication languages often contain values, types, and objects that involve  a great deal of interaction with their environment - tings like <i>closures that access mutable state</i>, <i>lambdas with free variables</i>, and <i>pointers</i>.  Other values have potential to mutate as you use them, such as <i>stateful objects</i>; these are especially difficult to store or share, as doing so essentially requires either continuous cache maintenance or time-sharing... either of which is difficult to achieve if one wishes to persist the values.  Other values imply special dependencies for their use - e.g. scripts require embedded interpreters, filenames require one be on the right filesystem, BLOBs require codecs, anything that requires <i>explicit</i> post-processing (e.g. parsing or translation).  These dependencies and interactions can make these values and types far less easy to usefully share.  ",
